🚀 Week 1 – Day 3 Python Data Types & Operators 🐍🔢⚡

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🧠 Introduction

Data types define the type of value stored in a variable.

Operators are symbols used to perform operations on values and variables.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

📦 1. Python Data Types

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 What is a Data Type?

```text id="datatype_def"
A data type specifies the kind of value a variable can store.
````

---

🎯 Why Data Types Matter

✔ Efficient memory usage
✔ Better program execution
✔ Helps avoid errors
✔ Important for calculations

---

🔢 Main Python Data Types

| Data Type | Description             | Example          |
| --------- | ----------------------- | ---------------- |
| `int`     | Integer numbers         | `10`             |
| `float`   | Decimal numbers         | `3.14`           |
| `str`     | Text/String             | `"Python"`       |
| `bool`    | True/False values       | `True`           |
| `list`    | Ordered collection      | `[1, 2, 3]`      |
| `tuple`   | Immutable collection    | `(1, 2)`         |
| `set`     | Unordered unique values | `{1, 2, 3}`      |
| `dict`    | Key-value pairs         | `{"name":"Sam"}` |

---

💻 Integer Example

```python id="int_example"
age = 21

print(age)
print(type(age))
```

---

💻 Float Example

```python id="float_example"
pi = 3.14159

print(pi)
print(type(pi))
```

---

💻 String Example

```python id="string_example"
language = "Python"

print(language)
print(type(language))
```

---

💻 Boolean Example

```python id="boolean_example"
is_python_fun = True

print(is_python_fun)
print(type(is_python_fun))
```

---

📋 List Data Type

Lists store multiple values.

```python id="list_example"
numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40]

print(numbers)
print(type(numbers))
```

---

📦 Tuple Data Type

Tuples are immutable.

```python id="tuple_example"
coordinates = (10, 20)

print(coordinates)
print(type(coordinates))
```

---

🔄 Set Data Type

Sets store unique values.

```python id="set_example"
unique_numbers = {1, 2, 3, 3, 4}

print(unique_numbers)
```

---

🗂️ Dictionary Data Type

Dictionaries store data in key-value form.

```python id="dict_example"
student = {
    "name": "Saakshi",
    "age": 22
}

print(student)
print(type(student))
```

---

🔄 Type Conversion

Type conversion changes one data type into another.

---

💻 Example

```python id="type_conversion_example"
num = "100"

converted_num = int(num)

print(converted_num)
print(type(converted_num))
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

⚡ 2. Python Operators

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 What is an Operator?

```text id="operator_def"
An operator is a symbol used to perform operations on values or variables.
```

---

➕ Arithmetic Operators

| Operator | Meaning        | Example  |
| -------- | -------------- | -------- |
| `+`      | Addition       | `5 + 2`  |
| `-`      | Subtraction    | `5 - 2`  |
| `*`      | Multiplication | `5 * 2`  |
| `/`      | Division       | `5 / 2`  |
| `%`      | Modulus        | `5 % 2`  |
| `//`     | Floor Division | `5 // 2` |
| `**`     | Power          | `5 ** 2` |

---

💻 Arithmetic Example

```python id="arithmetic_example"
a = 10
b = 3

print(a + b)
print(a - b)
print(a * b)
print(a / b)
print(a % b)
print(a // b)
print(a ** b)
```

---

⚖️ Comparison Operators

| Operator | Meaning               |
| -------- | --------------------- |
| `==`     | Equal to              |
| `!=`     | Not equal to          |
| `>`      | Greater than          |
| `<`      | Less than             |
| `>=`     | Greater than or equal |
| `<=`     | Less than or equal    |

---

💻 Comparison Example

```python id="comparison_example"
x = 10
y = 20

print(x == y)
print(x != y)
print(x < y)
print(x > y)
```

---

🔗 Logical Operators

| Operator | Meaning              |
| -------- | -------------------- |
| `and`    | Both conditions true |
| `or`     | At least one true    |
| `not`    | Reverse condition    |

---

💻 Logical Operator Example

```python id="logical_example"
a = True
b = False

print(a and b)
print(a or b)
print(not a)
```

---

📝 Assignment Operators

| Operator | Example  |
| -------- | -------- |
| `=`      | `x = 5`  |
| `+=`     | `x += 2` |
| `-=`     | `x -= 2` |
| `*=`     | `x *= 2` |
| `/=`     | `x /= 2` |

---

💻 Assignment Example

```python id="assignment_example"
x = 10

x += 5

print(x)
```

---

🧠 Membership Operators

| Operator | Meaning             |
| -------- | ------------------- |
| `in`     | Present in sequence |
| `not in` | Not present         |

---

💻 Membership Example

```python id="membership_example"
languages = ["Python", "Java", "C++"]

print("Python" in languages)
print("Go" not in languages)
```

---

🆔 Identity Operators

| Operator | Meaning          |
| -------- | ---------------- |
| `is`     | Same object      |
| `is not` | Different object |

---

💻 Identity Example

```python id="identity_example"
x = [1, 2]
y = x

print(x is y)
```

---

🎯 Operator Precedence

Python follows operator priority rules.

Example:

```python id="precedence_example"
result = 10 + 5 * 2

print(result)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="precedence_output"
20
```

Because multiplication happens first.

---

🚀 Mini Practice Program

```python id="practice_program"
num1 = int(input("Enter first number: "))
num2 = int(input("Enter second number: "))

print("Addition:", num1 + num2)
print("Multiplication:", num1 * num2)
print("Greater:", num1 > num2)
```

